The United Nations Security Council yesterday heard that there&#8217;s a need for continued international attention. PRETORIA - The United Nations peacekeeping chief says despite improving security in the capital of the Central African Republic, concerns remain in other parts of the country.The United Nations Security Council yesterday heard that there s a need for continued international attention.Head of UN peacekeeping Herv Ladsous says it s concerning that clashes in the centre of the country have assumed ethnic overtones. The Front populaire pour la renaissance de la Centrafrique and the Union pour la paix en Centrafrique are outside an ongoing dialogue established by the country s President Faustin Archange Touadera, together with other armed groups who have made progress in areas including disarmament, demobilisation and reintegration.Ladsous told the Security Council that an international conference on CAR, held in Brussels in November last year, generated $2,2 billion in pledges and spoke of the peace-building commission s work in the country.